The chemicals exist in items such as credit cards
PA
Rhoda Buchanan
Last updated at 1:06AM, February 20 2013
The United Nations has called for an investigation into hormone-disrupting chemicals found in everyday objects, which scientists believe could explain problems ranging from poor semen quality to low birthweight.
Evidence is mounting that endocrine disrupting chemicals (EDCs), which exist in pesticides, electronics, cosmetics and food additives, become a health risk when they enter the environment, the UN Environment Programme and World Health Organisation said in a report. Officials said that EDCs, which are found in items including toys, PVC flooring, car dashboards and credit cards, have not been fully studied.
